---
<BaseLayout title="Architecture — Codebolt" navbarVariant="solid" site={site} navigation={navigation}>
  <PageHeader
    title="Architecture"
    subtitle="Codebolt is built from the ground up as an agent platform, not an editor with agents bolted on."
  />
  <DiagramSection
    heading="The Platform Stack"
    layers={[{"label":"Interface Layer — IDE, TUI, CLI, Web","tag":"surface","style":"surface"},{"label":"Communication Layer — Agent, Plugin, Client SDKs","tag":"runtime","style":"runtime"},{"label":"Coordination Layer — Stigmergy, Deliberation, Pheromones","tag":"coordination","style":"drift"},{"label":"Intelligence Layer — Drift Engine, Narrative Versioning (Rust)","tag":"Rust","style":"versioning"},{"label":"Infrastructure Layer — Governance, Environments, Providers","tag":"core","style":"governance"}]}
    annotation="Other tools are Layer 1-2. Agent frameworks are Layer 2 only. Codebolt is all five."
  />
  <Accordion
    heading="Platform Architecture"
    items={[{"question":"Three Communication Channels","answer":"Codebolt exposes three communication paths. The Agent Channel (codeboltjs) lets external agents connect as child processes with 63+ API modules. The Plugin Channel (plugin SDK) provides three sub-channels — WebSocket for actions, multiplexed events for real-time updates, and HTTP REST for CRUD — enabling applications to run inside the platform without separate agent instances. The Client Channel (client SDK) connects UIs (Electron, Web, TUI) with 72 REST modules and 33 WebSocket modules. Each channel serves a distinct purpose: agents do work, plugins connect the platform to the world, clients give you control."},{"question":"HostBridge: Run Anywhere","answer":"The core engine never calls platform APIs directly. Instead, it defines a HostBridge interface for process spawning, SQLite, Kuzu graph DB, and ONNX inference. Each runtime implements its own bridge: Electron uses UtilityProcess and TypeORM, CLI uses child_process and better-sqlite3, TUI connects via WebSocket proxy. This is how one codebase powers a desktop IDE, a CLI tool, and a headless server with identical capabilities."},{"question":"The Provider/Environment System","answer":"Providers manage compute environments. The built-in Docker provider creates containers running a dockerserver that connects back to the main instance. Each environment has a full lifecycle — CREATED, STARTING, RUNNING, STOPPING, STOPPED — with heartbeat monitoring. The Narrative Engine snapshots workspace state per-environment, and git bundles transfer state between them. The main system controls environment spawning and closing, and even agents have access to environment management. This enables hierarchical setups where one Codebolt instance orchestrates many others."},{"question":"Agent Lifecycle","answer":"Agents are discovered from a marketplace API, cached locally, and spawned as child processes. They connect via codeboltjs, call waitForReady(), then handle messages and invoke API modules. The platform manages agent registration, status tracking, and lifecycle events. Agents can spawn child agents, participate in swarms, join deliberation councils, create review-merge requests, and manage other agents — all through the SDK."},{"question":"Plugin Lifecycle","answer":"Plugins are discovered from project .codeboltPlugins/ directories and global ~/.codebolt/plugins/. Each plugin declares itself in package.json with a codebolt.plugin key. The PluginProcessManager handles loading, starting, stopping, and trigger-based auto-start. Plugins receive a PluginContext with their ID, directory, and manifest. They can perform any action an agent can, plus subscribe to real-time events and make HTTP API calls."}]}
  />
  <Accordion
    heading="Research Foundations"
    items={[{"question":"Stigmergy-Based Coordination","answer":"Traditional multi-agent systems rely on direct message passing — agents send instructions to each other, creating fragile coupling and scaling bottlenecks. Codebolt uses stigmergy: agents communicate indirectly through structured shared state. Each agent reads from and writes to a shared environment, allowing coordination to emerge without explicit messaging. This is how biological swarms scale to millions of agents — and it's how Codebolt scales beyond the limits of message-passing architectures."},{"question":"Pheromone-Based Task Ownership","answer":"Inspired by ant colony optimization, agents deposit 'pheromones' on tasks and files to signal interest and ownership. Pheromone types are configurable. The aggregation system handles conflict resolution when multiple agents show interest in the same work. Lock/unlock mechanisms provide exclusive access when needed. This prevents the coordination breakdown that happens when agents independently decide to work on the same code."},{"question":"The Narrative Engine (Rust)","answer":"A Rust-based 'flight recorder' that maintains a complete record of agent actions, decisions, and reasoning. It uses shadow git for snapshot versioning with a narrative hierarchy: Objective → Thread → Agent Run → Snapshot. Per-thread commit branches (refs/threads/<thread_id>) provide agent-specific history. Git bundles transfer snapshots between environments. Every change carries its narrative — the intent behind it, not just the diff."},{"question":"Drift Tracking: Two-Level Architecture","answer":"Drift tracking operates at two levels. Local Rust engine instances assess drift within individual agent contexts — structural drift (architecture diverging from plan), scope drift (features expanding beyond intent), constraint drift (violations of specified rules), and coverage drift (gaps in implementation). The global JavaScript coordination layer aggregates these signals across all agents, detecting systemic drift patterns that no single agent would catch alone."},{"question":"Agent Deliberation Council","answer":"Agents participate in structured deliberations: propose options, respond, vote, and reach consensus. Deliberation types include decision, review, brainstorm, approval, and vote. All deliberations are stored per-project and fully traceable. This enables agents to make architectural decisions collectively rather than having one agent guess at the right approach."}]}
  />
  <Accordion
    heading="Published Research"
    items={[{"question":"Swarm Versioning","icon":"→","answer":"A framework for versioning agent-generated code at scale, using narrative-preserving git tree structures."},{"question":"IntentGraph","icon":"→","answer":"Modeling developer intent as a directed graph for drift detection in multi-agent software engineering."},{"question":"StigmergySwarm","icon":"→","answer":"Applying stigmergic coordination patterns from biological swarm intelligence to multi-agent code generation."}]}
  />
  <CtaBlock
    heading="Convinced by the engineering."
    buttons={[{"label":"Get Started","href":"/pricing","variant":"primary"},{"label":"Read the Docs","href":"https://docs.codebolt.ai","variant":"secondary","external":true}]}
  />
</BaseLayout>
